04793nam a22007575i 9780231528030DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011008941  a(OCoLC)979832180  a97802315280307 a10.7312/tabb158422doi  a(DE-B1597)459372  a(OCoLC)778616979  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHB501b.T313 2012 4aHB501b.T313 2015 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a3322231 aTabb, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Restructuring of Capitalism in Our Time /cWilliam Tabb. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Centrality of Finance -- t2. Financialization and Social Structures of Accumulation -- t3. Realism in Financial Markets -- t4. The Shadow of the Financial System -- t5. The Coming Apart -- t6. Rescue and the Limits of Regulation -- t7. Nations, Globalization, and Financialization -- t8. The Present in History -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aActions taken by the United States and other countries during the Great Recession focused on restoring the viability of major financial institutions while guaranteeing debt and stimulating growth. Once the markets stabilized, the United States enacted regulatory reforms that ultimately left basic economic structures unchanged. At the same time, the political class pursued austerity measures to curb the growing national debt. Drawing on the economic theories of Keynes and Minsky and applying them to the modern evolution of American banking and finance, William K. Tabb offers a chilling prediction about future crises and the structural factors inhibiting true reform.Tabb follows the rise of banking practices and financial motives in America over the past thirty years and the simultaneous growth of a shadow industry of hedge funds, private equity firms, and financial innovations such as derivatives. He marks the shift from an American economy based primarily on the production of goods and nonfinancial services to one characterized by financialization, then shows how these developments, perspectives, and approaches not only contributed to the recent financial crisis but also prevented the enactment of effective regulatory reform. He incisively analyzes the damage that increasing unsustainable debt and excessive risk-taking has done to our financial system and expands his critique to a discussion of world systems and globalization. Revealing the willful blind spots of mainstream finance theory, Tabb moves beyond an economic model reliant on debt expansion and dangerous levels of leverage, proposing instead a social structure of accumulation that places economic justice over profit and, more practically, institutes an inclusive, sustainable model for growth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBanks and banking. 0aCapitalismxPolitical aspects. 0aFinancexLaw and legislation. 0aFinancial crises. 0aMonetary policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/tabb1584240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231528030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231528030/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE